{"parse":{"title":"Center versus periphery","pageid":9646053,"revid":729521411,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:252px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:H%C3%B4gen_Sh%C3%BBken-ron_theory_diagram.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/3/39/H%C3%B4gen_Sh%C3%BBken-ron_theory_diagram.jpg/250px-H%C3%B4gen_Sh%C3%BBken-ron_theory_diagram.jpg\" width=\"250\" height=\"87\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/3/39/H%C3%B4gen_Sh%C3%BBken-ron_theory_diagram.jpg/375px-H%C3%B4gen_Sh%C3%BBken-ron_theory_diagram.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/3/39/H%C3%B4gen_Sh%C3%BBken-ron_theory_diagram.jpg/500px-H%C3%B4gen_Sh%C3%BBken-ron_theory_diagram.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"598\" data-file-height=\"207\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:H%C3%B4gen_Sh%C3%BBken-ron_theory_diagram.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Simple illustration of Center versus Periphery theory over time</div></div></div>\n<p><b>Center versus periphery</b><span style=\"font-weight: normal\">&#32;(<span lang=\"ja\">\u65b9\u8a00\u5468\u570f\u8ad6</span><span style=\"display:none\">,</span>&#32;<i>H\u014dgen-Sh\u016bken-Ron</i>, lit. \"Surrounding-zones dialect theory\")</span> is a linguistic theory put forward by Japanese folklorist <a href=\"/wiki/Yanagita_Kunio\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Yanagita Kunio\">Yanagita Kunio</a> explaining the usage of certain words in a language used in some regions while not in others. The theory may also explain the existence of other <a href=\"/wiki/Culture\" title=\"Culture\">cultural</a> features, or lack thereof, in differing regions; though it was specifically created to address linguistic differences.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Overview\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Overview</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Origin\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Origin</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Example\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Example</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Overview\">Overview</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Center_versus_periphery&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Overview\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>In general, the theory states that new words, often <a href=\"/wiki/Synonyms\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Synonyms\">synonyms</a>, are created in influential areas and cultural centers. Over time, these words gradually move outward to less culturally influential areas in a <a href=\"/wiki/Ripple_(fluid_dynamics)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Ripple (fluid dynamics)\">ripple pattern</a>. Over time, the new words may travel a great distance. However, during their slow progression outwards from the cultural center, new words are also being created and gradually moving outwards. New words may not have the \"momentum\" necessary to propagate to all areas where the language is used. Typically, areas that are farthest away from a cultural center will possess only the oldest form of a word and no others, though the new words often still remain active in the cultural center where they were created, along with other synonym variations.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Origin\">Origin</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Center_versus_periphery&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Origin\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>This theory was postulated by <a href=\"/wiki/Yanagita_Kunio\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Yanagita Kunio\">Yanagita Kunio</a> to explain the existence of some words in cultural centers, such as the capital of <a href=\"/wiki/Japan\" title=\"Japan\">Japan</a>, during various stages of the nation's history, and the lack of those such words in non-cultural centers. It is not certain if his postulate was the first to describe such cultural patterns in general; or merely with respect to language.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Example\">Example</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Center_versus_periphery&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Example\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:202px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:H%C3%B4gen_Sh%C3%BBken-ron_theory_example.png\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/49/H%C3%B4gen_Sh%C3%BBken-ron_theory_example.png/200px-H%C3%B4gen_Sh%C3%BBken-ron_theory_example.png\" width=\"200\" height=\"221\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/49/H%C3%B4gen_Sh%C3%BBken-ron_theory_example.png/300px-H%C3%B4gen_Sh%C3%BBken-ron_theory_example.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/4/49/H%C3%B4gen_Sh%C3%BBken-ron_theory_example.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"364\" data-file-height=\"402\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:H%C3%B4gen_Sh%C3%BBken-ron_theory_example.png\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Example word for the Center versus Periphery over time</div></div></div>\n<p>One phenomenon the theory attempts to explain, for example, is the <a href=\"/wiki/Japanese_language\" title=\"Japanese language\">Japanese</a> word for <a href=\"/wiki/Snail\" title=\"Snail\">snail</a>, particularly prior to the <a href=\"/wiki/Meiji_period\" title=\"Meiji period\">Meiji period</a>. In <a href=\"/wiki/Kyoto\" title=\"Kyoto\">Kyoto</a>, the capital of Japan around the time of the <a href=\"/wiki/Edo_period\" title=\"Edo period\">Edo period</a>, there were as many as four different words for snail: <i>dedemushi</i> (\u3067\u3067\u3080\u3057), <i>maimai</i> (\u307e\u3044\u307e\u3044), <i>katatsumuri</i> (\u304b\u305f\u3064\u3080\u308a), and <i>tsuburi</i> (\u3064\u3076\u308a). In the areas outside the capital, not all of these words existed. As one traveled farther from the capital, the number of synonyms employed decreased. In the farthest reaches of Japan in the North and the South, typically only one word for \"snail\" was used. <a href=\"/wiki/Coincidence\" title=\"Coincidence\">Coincidentally</a>, often the same single word existed in both places (in this case <i>tsuburi</i> (\u3064\u3076\u308a)), despite the great distance between the regions. Some <a href=\"/wiki/Linguists\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Linguists\">linguists</a> have taken this existence of some words in the farthest regions from cultural centers as an indication of the age of certain of these words.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Center_versus_periphery&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><cite class=\"citation book\">Yanagita, Kunio (1930). <i>On snails (in Japanese)</i>. Toko Shoin.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=On+snails+%28in+Japanese%29&amp;rft.pub=Toko+Shoin&amp;rft.date=1930&amp;rft.au=Yanagita%2C+Kunio&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACenter+versus+periphery\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li></ul>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1271\nCached time: 20180909074257\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.064 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.089 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 162/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 1639/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 543/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 9/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 0/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.028/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 1.38 MB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%   72.052      1 -total\n 54.91%   39.561      1 Template:Nihongo\n 44.94%   32.378      1 Template:Cite_book\n 44.26%   31.893      1 Template:Category_handler\n  3.57%    2.573      2 Template:Trim\n  2.89%    2.085      2 Template:Yesno\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:9646053-0!canonical and timestamp 20180909074257 and revision id 729521411\n -->\n</div>"},"langlinks":[{"lang":"ja","url":"https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E6%96%B9%E8%A8%80%E5%91%A8%E5%9C%8F%E8%AB%96","langname":"Japanese","autonym":"\u65e5\u672c\u8a9e","*":"\u65b9\u8a00\u5468\u570f\u8ad6"}],"categories":[{"sortkey":"","hidden":"","*":"Articles_containing_Japanese-language_text"},{"sortkey":"","*":"Sociolinguistics"},{"sortkey":"","*":"Historical_linguistics"},{"sortkey":"","*":"Japanese_language"}],"links":[{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Coincidence"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Culture"},{"ns"